sic/news/220540 |title=\u3055\u304f\u3089\u5b66\u9662\u304c\"13\u4eba\"\u3067\u604b\u30c0\u30f3\u30b9\u3001\u68ee\u30cf\u30e4\u30b739\u6b73\u300c\u3044\u3044\u4eba\u751f\u3060\u3063\u305f\u300d - \u97f3\u697d\u30ca\u30bf\u30ea\u30fc |last=Inc. |first=Natasha |date=2017-02-13 |website=\u97f3\u697d\u30ca\u30bf\u30ea\u30fc |language=ja |access-date=2018-10-30}}</ref> and [[Babymetal]].<ref name=metal/> She was the stage director and choreographer for Japan's cultural presentation at the [[2016 Summer Olympics closing ceremony]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://aramajapan.com/news/shiina-ringo-to-help-produce-tokyos-handover-ceremony-at-the-rio-olympics/54208/|title=Shiina Ringo to Help Produce Tokyo's Handover Ceremony at the Rio Olympics {{!}} ARAMA! JAPAN|date=2016-01-26|work=ARAMA! JAPAN|access-date=2017-11-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.mikiko0811.net Official website] {{in lang|ja}}\n* [https://twitter.com/mikiko_san?lang=en Twitter]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/mikiko_san/ Instagram]\n\n{{Sakura Gakuin}}\n{{Babymetal}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mikiko}}\n[[Category:Japanese choreographers]]\n[[Category:Japanese female dancers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Amuse, Inc. talents]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n\n\n{{Dance-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "PeepleLikeYou", "label": "safe", "comment": "Mark dead link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mikiko_(choreographer)"}
{"title_page": "Terry Doran", "text_new": "{{short description|British music manager}}\n'''Terry Doran''' (1936 \u2013 19 April 2020) was an English pop band manager, known for managing the band [[Grapefruit (band)|Grapefruit]] and singer [[Mary Hopkin]], as well as having a business association with [[the Beatles]]. With the Beatles' own manager, [[Brian Epstein]], he co-owned Brydor Cars, which supplied sportscars to many figures in the [[Swinging London]] era, including members of the Beatles and [[the Rolling Stones]]. Doran managed the Beatles' company [[Apple Publishing]] in the late 1960s. Following the band's break-up in 1970, he worked as the estate manager at [[George Harrison]]'s [[Friar Park]] property.\n\nHe is often cited as the inspiration behind the line \"Meeting a man from the motor trade\" in the Beatles' 1967 song \"[[She's Leaving Home]]\", although [[Paul McCartney]] later denied the story.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=316}} Doran suggested the verb \"fill\" in the line \"Now they know how many holes it takes to fill the Albert Hall\", from \"[[A Day in the Life]]\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Alan |first1=Aldridge|title=The Beatles Illustrated Lyrics|title-link=The Beatles Illustrated Lyrics|date=1969 |publisher=Black Dog & Leventhal Publishers |isbn=1-57912-058-X |page=29}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDoran met [[Brian Epstein]], who was then managing the Epstein family's NEMS record stores, in a Liverpool pub in 1959 and the pair became immediate friends. Beatles historian [[Mark Lewisohn]] describes Doran as \"a car salesman with a sharp mind and a ready Liverpool wit\".{{sfn|Lewisohn|2013|p=277}}\n\nHe met the Beatles in the early 1960s, shortly after Epstein had become the band's manager.{{sfn|Lewisohn|2013|p=570}} Doran worked for Hawthorne Motors, a [[car dealership]] in [[Warrington]], and sold the first car owned by a member of the Beatles \u2013 a blue [[Ford Anglia]] \u2013 to [[George Harrison]], the youngest member of the group.{{sfn|Lewisohn|2013|pp=618, 683}} In exchange for the reasonable terms offered by Doran, Harrison agreed to pose with his bandmates [[John Lennon]] and [[Paul McCartney]], and the car, in an advertisement for Hawthorne.{{sfn|Lewisohn|2013|pp=618, 683}} The ad appeared in the local ''[[Mersey Beat]]'' music newspaper in July 1962, at a time when the Beatles' popularity had yet to expand beyond the north of England and the club circuit in Hamburg.{{sfn|Lewisohn|2013|p=683}} Doran then supplied the band \u2013 who were soon to fire [[Pete Best]] as their drummer and probably lose Best's van as their means of transportion to gigs \u2013 with an eight-seater Ford Thames van, which NEMS purchased on the group's behalf.{{sfn|Lewisohn|2013|p=684}}\n\nIn 1963, Doran moved to London when Epstein relocated NEMS there with the growth of the Beatles' operation. He shared a flat in [[Shepherd Market]] in [[Mayfair]] with [[BBC Radio]] producer [[Bernie Andrews]].{{sfn|Clayson|2003|p=151}} Doran co-owned (with Epstein) and ran the car dealership Brydor, based in [[Hounslow]], west of London. His customers included the Beatles, who acquired their [[Mini]]s through Brydor.<ref name=\"Harding/TSC\">{{cite web|first=G.H.|last=Harding|title=The Glorious Corner\" > \"Terry Doran RIP|url=https://t2conline.com/the-glorious-corner-56/|website=Times Square Chronicles|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> He also supplied the band and other music celebrities with upmarket cars.<ref>{{cite news|title=Terry Doran obituary|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/terry-doran-obituary-hkxd8r2b5|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=22 April 2020|p=52|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1967, he was appointed manager of the Beatles' new company [[Apple Publishing]].{{sfn|Everett|1999|p=144}} Having signed songwriter [[Alexander Young|George Alexander]] to the company, he introduced Alexander to his subsequent bandmates in the group [[Grapefruit (band)|Grapefruit]].<ref name=\"Harding/TSC\" /> Doran managed Grapefruit, and his friendship with the Beatles ensured that Lennon and McCartney assisted the band in recording their first single.{{sfn|Everett|1999|p=144}} In December that year, he secured a deal with American producer and songwriter [[Terry Melcher]]'s music company for Apple to oversee Melcher's publishing concerns in the UK.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Beatles' Firm, Melcher Deal|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=ZygEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=%22Terry+Doran%22+obituary&source=bl&ots=0EhMmUZb7K&sig=ACfU3U1Kv3ahwjVyrlY-VOqpOPXCHKlIZA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiD1frp4IDpAhVg4jgGHRs2BUs4FBDoATADegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=%22Terry%20Doran%22%20obituary&f=false|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=23 December 1967|p=4|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThrough Doran's introduction, Liverpool singer [[Jackie Lomax]] became one of the first acts signed to the Beatles' record company, [[Apple Records]].{{sfn|Clayson|2003|pp=239\u201340}} In November 1968, when Grapefruit parted ways with Apple Publishing, Doran commented in ''[[The Sunday People|The People]]'': \"I like the Beatles as friends, but not bosses ... there's too much driftwood at Apple.\"{{sfn|Miles|2001|p=320}} He enjoyed success as the manager of Apple Records artist [[Mary Hopkin]], although Hopkin later said she was highly dissatisfied with his management.{{sfn|Everett|1999|p=208}}\n\nIn early 1970, Doran became estate manager at Harrison's new property, [[Friar Park]], in [[Oxfordshire]].{{sfn|Clayson|2003|p=319}}{{sfn|Harrison|2002|p=71fn}} He assisted Harrison in renovating the Victorian-era house and gardens, much of which was in a state of disrepair.{{sfn|O'Dell|2009|pp=130, 136}} Chris O'Dell, who worked as Harrison's assistant at the time, said that Doran's humour provided levity in the household when Harrison became prone to sermonising on his Hindu beliefs. Doran was represented in a [[Krishna]]-inspired painting that [[Tom Wilkes]] designed as an insert poster for Harrison's ''[[All Things Must Pass]]'' triple album, although the poster was ultimately not used.{{sfn|Spizer|2005|pp=226, 228}} He worked at Harrison's company Oops Publishing until resigning in February 1975.{{sfn|Badman|2001|p=151}}\n\n==Death==\nDoran's death, at age 80, was announced by Mark Lewisohn on 19 April 2020. Lewisohn did not provide a precise date nor details on the cause of death, but wrote: \"Not only the 'man from the motor trade' in She's Leaving Home, also a Scouse pal of Brian Epstein (manager of their Brydor Cars business), mate to all the Beatles, a laugh, joint-roller and merry tripper, ran Apple Music and was George's PA at Friar Park.\"<ref name=\"BCB/DoranDies\" />\n\n[[Pattie Boyd]], Harrison's ex-wife, wrote: \"So saddened to hear of the passing of Terry Doran. Terry was a major part of my life at Friar Park and he was also very close to George.\"<ref name=\"BCB/DoranDies\">{{cite web|author=Best Classic Bands staff|title=Beatles Associate Terry Doran Dies|url=https://bestclassicbands.com/terry-doran-beatles-dead-4-19-200/|website=Best Classic Bands|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Badman|first=Keith|title=The Beatles Diary Volume 2: After the Break-Up 1970\u20132001|publisher=Omnibus Press|location=London|year=2001|isbn=978-0-7119-8307-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|author=The Beatles|authorlink=The Beatles|title=The Beatles Anthology|publisher=Chronicle Books|location=San Francisco, CA|year=2000|isbn=0-8118-2684-8|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/beatlesanthology0000unse}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Boyd|first1=Pattie|authorlink=Pattie Boyd|last2=with Junor|first2=Penny|year=2007|title=Wonderful Today: The Autobiography|location=London|publisher=Headline Review|isbn=978-0-7553-1646-5|ref={{SfnRef|Boyd|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Brown|first1=Peter|authorlink=Peter Brown (music industry)|last2=Gaines|first2=Steven|authorlink2=Steven Gaines|title=The Love You Make: An Insider's Story of the Beatles|publisher=New American Library|location=New York, NY|year=2002|origyear=1983|isbn=978-0-4512-0735-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Clayson|first=Alan|authorlink=Alan Clayson|title=George Harrison|publisher=Sanctuary|location=London|year=2003|isbn=1-86074-489-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Everett|first=Walter|authorlink=Walter Everett (musicologist)|year=1999|title=The Beatles as Musicians: Revolver Through the Anthology| publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York, NY|isbn=0-19-512941-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Goldman|first=Albert|authorlink=Albert Goldman|title=The Lives of John Lennon|year=2001|origyear=1988|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, IL|isbn=978-1-55652-399-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Harrison|first=George|authorlink=George Harrison|title=I, Me, Mine|publisher=Chronicle Books|location=San Francisco, CA|year=2002|origyear=1980|isbn=978-0-8118-5900-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ingham|first=Chris|year=2006|title=The Rough Guide to the Beatles'' (2nd edn)''|publisher=Rough Guides|location=London|isbn=978-1-84353-720-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Lennon|first=Cynthia|authorlink=Cynthia Lennon|title=John|year=2005|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton|location=London|isbn=0-340895128|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Lewisohn|first=Mark|authorlink=Mark Lewisohn|year=2013|title=All These Years: Tune In|publisher=Little, Brown|location=London|isbn=978-0-316-72960-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=MacDonald|first=Ian|year=1998|authorlink=Ian MacDonald|title=Revolution in the Head: The Beatles' Records and the Sixties|publisher=Pimlico|location=London|isbn=978-0-7126-6697-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Miles|first=Barry|authorlink=Barry Miles|title=Paul McCartney: Many Years from Now|year=1997|publisher=Henry Holt|location=New York, NY|isbn=0-8050-5249-6|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/paulmccartneyman00mile}}\n* {{cite book|last=Miles|first=Barry|title=The Beatles Diary Volume 1: The Beatles Years|year=2001|publisher=Omnibus Press|location=London|isbn=0-7119-8308-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Norman|first=Philip|authorlink=Philip Norman (author)|title=Shout!: The Beatles in Their Generation|publisher=Fireside|location=New York, NY|year=1996|origyear=1981|isbn=0-684-83067-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Norman|first=Philip|title=John Lennon: The Life|year=2008|publisher=Ecco|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0-06-075402-0|url=https://archive.org/details/johnlennonlife00norm}}\n* {{cite book|last1=O'Dell|first1=Chris|last2=with Ketcham|first2=Katherine|title=Miss O'Dell: My Hard Days and Long Nights with The Beatles, The Stones, Bob Dylan, Eric Clapton, and the Women They Loved|publisher=Touchstone|location=New York, NY|year=2009|isbn=978-1-4165-9093-4|ref={{SfnRef|O'Dell|2009}}|url=https://archive.org/details/missodellmyhardd00odel}}\n* {{cite book|first=Mark|last=Paytress|chapter=A Passage to India|year=2003|title=[[Mojo (magazine)#Special editions|Mojo Special Limited Edition]]: 1000 Days of Revolution (The Beatles' Final Years \u2013 Jan 1, 1968 to Sept 27, 1970)|location=London|publisher=[[Emap]]|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Spitz|first=Bob|authorlink=Bob Spitz|title=The Beatles: The Biography|url=https://archive.org/details/beatlesbiography00spit|url-access=registration|publisher=Little, Brown and Company|location=New York, NY|year=2005|isbn=978-0-316-80352-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Spizer|first=Bruce|authorlink=Bruce Spizer|title=The Beatles Solo on Apple Records|publisher=498 Productions|location=New Orleans, LA|year=2005|isbn=0-9662649-5-9|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs artist|Terry Doran}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doran, Terry}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:The Beatles]]\n[[Category:Music managers]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British music manager}}\n'''Terry Doran''' (1936 \u2013 19 April 2020) was an English pop band manager, known for managing the band [[Grapefruit (band)|Grapefruit]] and singer [[Mary Hopkin]], as well as having a business association with [[the Beatles]]. With the Beatles' own manager, [[Brian Epstein]], he co-owned Brydor Cars, which supplied sportscars to many figures in the [[Swinging London]] era, including members of the Beatles and [[the Rolling Stones]]. Doran managed the Beatles' company [[Apple Publishing]] in the late 1960s. Following the band's break-up in 1970, he worked as the estate manager at [[George Harrison]]'s [[Friar Park]] property.\n\nHe is often cited as the inspiration behind the line \"Meeting a man from the motor trade\" in the Beatles' 1967 song \"[[She's Leaving Home]]\", although [[Paul McCartney]] later denied the story.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=316}} Doran suggested the verb \"fill\" in the line \"Now they know how many holes it takes to fill the Albert Hall\", from \"[[A Day in the Life]]\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Alan |first1=Aldridge|title=The Beatles Illustrated Lyrics|title-link=The Beatles Illustrated Lyrics|date=1969 |publisher=Black Dog & Leventhal Publishers |isbn=1-57912-058-X |page=29}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDoran met [[Brian Epstein]], who was then managing the Epstein family's NEMS record stores, in a Liverpool pub in 1959 and the pair became immediate friends. Beatles historian [[Mark Lewisohn]] describes Doran as \"a car salesman with a sharp mind and a ready Liverpool wit\".{{sfn|Lewisohn|2013|p=277}}\n\nHe met the Beatles in the early 1960s, shortly after Epstein had become the band's manager.{{sfn|Lewisohn|2013|p=570}} Doran worked for Hawthorne Motors, a [[car dealership]] in [[Warrington]], and sold the first car owned by a member of the Beatles \u2013 a blue [[Ford Anglia]] \u2013 to [[George Harrison]], the youngest member of the group.{{sfn|Lewisohn|2013|pp=618, 683}} In exchange for the reasonable terms offered by Doran, Harrison agreed to pose with his bandmates [[John Lennon]] and [[Paul McCartney]], and the car, in an advertisement for Hawthorne.{{sfn|Lewisohn|2013|pp=618, 683}} The ad appeared in the local ''[[Mersey Beat]]'' music newspaper in July 1962, at a time when the Beatles' popularity had yet to expand beyond the north of England and the club circuit in Hamburg.{{sfn|Lewisohn|2013|p=683}} Doran then supplied the band \u2013 who were soon to fire [[Pete Best]] as their drummer and probably lose Best's van as their means of transportion to gigs \u2013 with an eight-seater Ford Thames van, which NEMS purchased on the group's behalf.{{sfn|Lewisohn|2013|p=684}}\n\nIn 1963, Doran moved to London when Epstein relocated NEMS there with the growth of the Beatles' operation. He shared a flat in [[Shepherd Market]] in [[Mayfair]] with [[BBC Radio]] producer [[Bernie Andrews]].{{sfn|Clayson|2003|p=151}} Doran co-owned (with Epstein) and ran the car dealership Brydor, based in [[Hounslow]], west of London. His customers included the Beatles, who acquired their [[Mini]]s through Brydor.<ref name=\"Harding/TSC\">{{cite web|first=G.H.|last=Harding|title=The Glorious Corner\" > \"Terry Doran RIP|url=https://t2conline.com/the-glorious-corner-56/|website=Times Square Chronicles|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> He also supplied the band and other music celebrities with upmarket cars.<ref>{{cite news|title=Terry Doran obituary|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/terry-doran-obituary-hkxd8r2b5|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=22 April 2020|p=52|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1967, he was appointed manager of the Beatles' new company [[Apple Publishing]].{{sfn|Everett|1999|p=144}} Having signed songwriter [[Alexander Young|George Alexander]] to the company, he introduced Alexander to his subsequent bandmates in the group [[Grapefruit (band)|Grapefruit]].<ref name=\"Harding/TSC\" /> Doran managed Grapefruit, and his friendship with the Beatles ensured that Lennon and McCartney assisted the band in recording their first single.{{sfn|Everett|1999|p=144}} In December that year, he secured a deal with American producer and songwriter [[Terry Melcher]]'s music company for Apple to oversee Melcher's publishing concerns in the UK.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Beatles' Firm, Melcher Deal|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=ZygEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=%22Terry+Doran%22+obituary&source=bl&ots=0EhMmUZb7K&sig=ACfU3U1Kv3ahwjVyrlY-VOqpOPXCHKlIZA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiD1frp4IDpAhVg4jgGHRs2BUs4FBDoATADegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=%22Terry%20Doran%22%20obituary&f=false|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=23 December 1967|p=4|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThrough Doran's introduction, Liverpool singer [[Jackie Lomax]] became one of the first acts signed to the Beatles' record company, [[Apple Records]].{{sfn|Clayson|2003|pp=239\u201340}} In November 1968, when Grapefruit parted ways with Apple Publishing, Doran commented in ''[[The Sunday People|The People]]'': \"I like the Beatles as friends, but not bosses ... there's too much driftwood at Apple.\"{{sfn|Miles|2001|p=320}} He enjoyed success as the manager of Apple Records artist [[Mary Hopkin]], although Hopkin later said she was highly dissatisfied with his management.{{sfn|Everett|1999|p=208}}\n\nIn early 1970, Doran became estate manager at Harrison's new property, [[Friar Park]], in [[Oxfordshire]].{{sfn|Clayson|2003|p=319}}{{sfn|Harrison|2002|p=71fn}} He assisted Harrison in renovating the Victorian-era house and gardens, much of which was in a state of disrepair.{{sfn|O'Dell|2009|pp=130, 136}} Chris O'Dell, who worked as Harrison's assistant at the time, said that Doran's humour provided levity in the household when Harrison became prone to sermonising on his Hindu beliefs. Doran was represented in a [[Krishna]]-inspired painting that [[Tom Wilkes]] designed as an insert poster for Harrison's ''[[All Things Must Pass]]'' triple album, although the poster was ultimately not used.{{sfn|Spizer|2005|pp=226, 228}} He worked at Harrison's company Oops Publishing until resigning in February 1975.{{sfn|Badman|2001|p=151}}\n\n==Death==\nDoran's death, at age 80, was announced by Mark Lewisohn on 19 April 2020. Lewisohn did not provide a precise date nor details on the cause of death, but wrote: \"Not only the 'man from the motor trade' in She's Leaving Home, also a Scouse pal of Brian Epstein (manager of their Brydor Cars business), mate to all the Beatles, a laugh, joint-roller and merry tripper, ran Apple Music and was George's PA at Friar Park.\"<ref name=\"BCB/DoranDies\" />\n\n[[Pattie Boyd]], Harrison's ex-wife, wrote: \"So saddened to hear of the passing of Terry Doran. Terry was a major part of my life at Friar Park and he was also very close to George.\"<ref name=\"BCB/DoranDies\">{{cite web|author=Best Classic Bands staff|title=Beatles Associate Terry Doran Dies|url=https://bestclassicbands.com/terry-doran-beatles-dead-4-19-200/|website=Best Classic Bands|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Badman|first=Keith|title=The Beatles Diary Volume 2: After the Break-Up 1970\u20132001|publisher=Omnibus Press|location=London|year=2001|isbn=978-0-7119-8307-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|author=The Beatles|authorlink=The Beatles|title=The Beatles Anthology|publisher=Chronicle Books|location=San Francisco, CA|year=2000|isbn=0-8118-2684-8|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/beatlesanthology0000unse}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Boyd|first1=Pattie|authorlink=Pattie Boyd|last2=with Junor|first2=Penny|year=2007|title=Wonderful Today: The Autobiography|location=London|publisher=Headline Review|isbn=978-0-7553-1646-5|ref={{SfnRef|Boyd|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Brown|first1=Peter|authorlink=Peter Brown (music industry)|last2=Gaines|first2=Steven|authorlink2=Steven Gaines|title=The Love You Make: An Insider's Story of the Beatles|publisher=New American Library|location=New York, NY|year=2002|origyear=1983|isbn=978-0-4512-0735-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Clayson|first=Alan|authorlink=Alan Clayson|title=George Harrison|publisher=Sanctuary|location=London|year=2003|isbn=1-86074-489-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Everett|first=Walter|authorlink=Walter Everett (musicologist)|year=1999|title=The Beatles as Musicians: Revolver Through the Anthology| publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York, NY|isbn=0-19-512941-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Goldman|first=Albert|authorlink=Albert Goldman|title=The Lives of John Lennon|year=2001|origyear=1988|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, IL|isbn=978-1-55652-399-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Harrison|first=George|authorlink=George Harrison|title=I, Me, Mine|publisher=Chronicle Books|location=San Francisco, CA|year=2002|origyear=1980|isbn=978-0-8118-5900-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ingham|first=Chris|year=2006|title=The Rough Guide to the Beatles'' (2nd edn)''|publisher=Rough Guides|location=London|isbn=978-1-84353-720-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Lennon|first=Cynthia|authorlink=Cynthia Lennon|title=John|year=2005|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton|location=London|isbn=0-340895128|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Lewisohn|first=Mark|authorlink=Mark Lewisohn|year=2013|title=All These Years: Tune In|publisher=Little, Brown|location=London|isbn=978-0-316-72960-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=MacDonald|first=Ian|year=1998|authorlink=Ian MacDonald|title=Revolution in the Head: The Beatles' Records and the Sixties|publisher=Pimlico|location=London|isbn=978-0-7126-6697-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Miles|first=Barry|authorlink=Barry Miles|title=Paul McCartney: Many Years from Now|year=1997|publisher=Henry Holt|location=New York, NY|isbn=0-8050-5249-6|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/paulmccartneyman00mile}}\n* {{cite book|last=Miles|first=Barry|title=The Beatles Diary Volume 1: The Beatles Years|year=2001|publisher=Omnibus Press|location=London|isbn=0-7119-8308-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Norman|first=Philip|authorlink=Philip Norman (author)|title=Shout!: The Beatles in Their Generation|publisher=Fireside|location=New York, NY|year=1996|origyear=1981|isbn=0-684-83067-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Norman|first=Philip|title=John Lennon: The Life|year=2008|publisher=Ecco|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0-06-075402-0|url=https://archive.org/details/johnlennonlife00norm}}\n* {{cite book|last1=O'Dell|first1=Chris|last2=with Ketcham|first2=Katherine|title=Miss O'Dell: My Hard Days and Long Nights with The Beatles, The Stones, Bob Dylan, Eric Clapton, and the Women They Loved|publisher=Touchstone|location=New York, NY|year=2009|isbn=978-1-4165-9093-4|ref={{SfnRef|O'Dell|2009}}|url=https://archive.org/details/missodellmyhardd00odel}}\n* {{cite book|first=Mark|last=Paytress|chapter=A Passage to India|year=2003|title=[[Mojo (magazine)#Special editions|Mojo Special Limited Edition]]: 1000 Days of Revolution (The Beatles' Final Years \u2013 Jan 1, 1968 to Sept 27, 1970)|location=London|publisher=[[Emap]]|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Spitz|first=Bob|authorlink=Bob Spitz|title=The Beatles: The Biography|url=https://archive.org/details/beatlesbiography00spit|url-access=registration|publisher=Little, Brown and Company|location=New York, NY|year=2005|isbn=978-0-316-80352-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Spizer|first=Bruce|authorlink=Bruce Spizer|title=The Beatles Solo on Apple Records|publisher=498 Productions|location=New Orleans, LA|year=2005|isbn=0-9662649-5-9|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n==External Links==\n* {{Discogs artist|Terry Doran}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doran, Terry}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:The Beatles]]\n[[Category:Music managers]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "All Hallow's Wraith", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal Links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terry_Doran"}
{"title_page": "Richard Hudson (American politician)", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{update|date=February 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2013}}\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Richard Hudson\n|image       = Richard Hudson official congressional photo.jpg\n|state       = [[North Carolina]]\n|district    = {{ushr|NC|8|8th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2013\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Larry Kissell]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1971|11|4}}\n|birth_place = [[Franklin, Virginia|Franklin]], [[Virginia]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Renee Hudson\n|education   = [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n|website     = {{url|hudson.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Richard Lane Hudson''' (born November 4, 1971) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] for [[North Carolina's 8th congressional district]] since 2013. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nHudson was born in [[Franklin, Virginia]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/richard-hudson--NC-H|title=Richard Hudson - Candidate for U.S. President, Republican Nomination - Election 2012|website=WSJ.com|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> but has lived in the [[Charlotte]] area since childhood.  He graduated from [[Myers Park High School]] in 1990, and from the [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]] in 1996,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=H001067|title=HUDSON, Richard - Biographical Information|website=bioguide.congress.gov|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> where he became a member of [[Kappa Alpha Order]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Congressman Richard Hudson|url=http://www.kappaalphaorder.org/2013/01/kas-in-public-service/hudson|publisher=Kappa Alpha Order|accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref> He has a bachelor's degree in political science and history, and served as student body president and president of the College Republicans.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Early career ==\nActive in politics for many years, Hudson served as district director for 8th District Congressman [[Robin Hayes]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncheroes.org/congressman-richard-hudson/|title=Congressman Richard Hudson {{!}} North Carolina Heroes' Fund|website=www.ncheroes.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> from 1999 to 2005.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thepilot.com/news/hudson-mills-vie-for-congressional-seat/article_0c321f38-8fde-11e6-a991-33c09f175c65.html|title=Hudson, Mills Vie for Congressional Seat|last=Editor|first=David Sinclair/Managing|work=The Pilot Newspaper|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en}}</ref>  At various times, he served on the staffs of Republicans [[Virginia Foxx]], [[John Carter (Texas)|John Carter]] and [[Mike Conaway]].<ref name=\":1\" /> He also served as communications director for the North Carolina Republican Party in the mid-1990s.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1996 he worked for Richard Vinroot's campaign for governor, and as campaign manager for Pat McCrory's run for governor in 2008.<ref name=\":0\" /> Hudson was the president of Cabarrus Marketing Group, a small business consulting and marketing company he started in 2011 and dissolved upon his election to Congress.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Richard Hudson, Official portrait, 113th Congress.jpg|thumb|Hudson during the [[113th United States Congress|113th Congress]]]]\n\n===2012 election===\nHudson ran for Congress in North Carolina's 8th congressional district. He won the Republican primary runoff on July 17, 2012, with 64% of the vote against opponent [[Scott Keadle]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Hudson to take on Kissell in U.S. District 8|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/07/17/3388590/hudson-to-take-on-kissell-in-us.html|accessdate=1 September 2012|newspaper=Charlotte Observer|date=18 July 2012|author=David Perlmutt and Lukas Johnson|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130119021645/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/07/17/3388590/hudson-to-take-on-kissell-in-us.html|archivedate=19 January 2013}}</ref> and faced Democratic incumbent [[Larry Kissell]] in November.  The district had been made significantly more Republican in redistricting, losing most of its share of Charlotte and picking up several heavily Republican areas northeast of the city.\n\nRichard Hudson spoke at the [[2012 Republican National Convention]] in [[Tampa, Florida]] on August 28, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Concord hopeful Hudson speaks role at Republican National Convention|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/08/28/3485275/concord-hopeful-hudson-speaks.html|accessdate=1 September 2012|newspaper=Charlotte Observer|date=28 August 2012|author=Franco Ordo\u00f1ez|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130119015557/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/08/28/3485275/concord-hopeful-hudson-speaks.html|archivedate=19 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nHudson defeated Kissell with 54 percent of the vote to Kissell's 46 percent and took office in January 2013.\n\n===2014 election===\nHudson was opposed by Antonio Blue in the general election and won 64.9% to 35.1% <ref>{{cite web|url=http://ballotpedia.org/Richard_Hudson|title=Richard Hudson - Ballotpedia|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===2018 election===\nHudson defeated Democrat Frank McNeill in the general election, winning 55.3% of the vote to McNeill's 44.7% <ref>{{cite web |title=North Carolina Election Results 2018 |url=https://www.politico.com/election-results/2018/north-carolina/ |website=politico.com |publisher=Politico |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Livestock, Rural Development, and Credit|Subcommittee on Livestock, Rural Development, and Credit]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]]\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training|Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Oversight, Investigations, and Management|Subcommittee on Oversight, Investigations, and Management]]\n*'''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===House Caucus's===\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hudson |first1=Richard |url=https://hudson.house.gov/committees-caucuses/ |website=Hudson.house.gov |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCongressman Hudson's 116th Congress Caucus Affiliations:\n\nAtlantic Offshore Energy Caucus, '''Co-Chair'''\n\nRepublican Study Committee\n\nRepublican Policy Committee\n\nAgriculture Policy Group, Chairman\n\nAgriculture and Rural America Task Force, '''Co-Chair'''\n\nPediatric Trauma Caucus, Co-Chair\n\nCongressional Prayer Caucus\n\nCongressional Textile Caucus\n\nCongressional Chicken Caucus\n\nCongressional German-American Caucus\n\nCongressional Peanut Caucus\n\nCongressional Sportsmen\u2019s Caucus, '''Vice-Chair'''\n\nCongressional Caucus on Foster Youth\n\nHouse Republican Israel Caucus\n\nHouse Special Operations Forces Caucus\n\nCongressional Army Aviation Caucus\n\nHouse National Guard and Reserve Components Caucus\n\nCongressional General Aviation Caucus\n\nCarbonated and Non-alcoholic (CAN) Caucus, '''Co-Chair'''\n\nBorder Security Caucus\n\nEnergy Savings Performance Caucus\n\nCongressional Cystic Fibrosis Caucus\n\nHouse Army Caucus\n\nDirect Selling Caucus, '''Co-Chair'''\n\nCongressional Motorsports Caucus\n\nHistorically Black Colleges and Universities Caucus\n\n===Legislation sponsored===\n* EPA et al. Appropriations Act, 2017 ({{USBill|114|HR|5538}}) Rep. Hudson proposed two amendments to (a) prohibit any of the funds appropriated to the EPA be used for any firearms or ammunition and (b) prohibit any of the funds appropriated to the EPA be used for employee or officer official travel by airplane.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/tipsheets/morning-energy/2016/07/let-the-wotus-court-fights-commence-215231|title=Let the WOTUS court fights commence!|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Hudson sponsored a bill requiring the [[Transportation Security Administration]] (TSA) to develop a comprehensive technology acquisition plan.<ref name=\"techreform1\">{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House to push tech reform at TSA |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/technology/191721-house-to-push-tech-reform-at-tsa|accessdate=4 December 2013|newspaper=The Hill|date=2 December 2013}}</ref> The [[Government Accountability Office]] and the [[Department of Homeland Security Office of Inspector General]] each found that the TSA's lack of a technology acquisition plan led to waste, excessive costs, and security failures.<ref name=\"techreform1\" /> The bill passed both Houses of Congress, becoming law on 12/18/2012.\n* Hudson sponsored a bill to improve airport security in reaction to the [[2013 Los Angeles International Airport shooting]].<ref name=\"LATweikel\">{{cite news|last1=Weikel|first1=Dan|title=House passes bill to improve airport security in wake of LAX shooting|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-airport-security-bill-20140722-story.html|accessdate=23 July 2014|publisher=LA Times|date=22 July 2014}}</ref> The bill was reintroduced by Rep. John Katko and became law in the 114th Congress.\n\n==Former Political positions==\n{{expand section|date=April 2019}}\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hudson |first1=Richard |title=Congressman Richard Hudson |url=https://hudson.house.gov/positions-and-awards/#dialog |website=Hudson.house.gov |publisher=Team Hudson |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n- Deputy Chairman, NRCC 2015-2016\n- Recruitment Chairman, NRCC 2015-2016\n- Agriculture Policy Chairman, House Republican Policy Committee 2015-2016\n- Chairman, that group that teaches women how to run for office\n- Rowan-Cabarrus Community College, Board of Trustees\n- UNC Charlotte Alumni Association, Board of Directors\n- UNC Charlotte Kappa Alpha Order, Alumni Chapter President\n- West Cabarrus YMCA, Board of Managers\n- Concord Jaycees, Board of Directors \n- 2014 Grand Marshall, National Hot Rod Association 4-Wide Nationals\n\n==Awards==\n\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hudson |first1=Richard |title=Congressman Richard Hudson |url=https://hudson.house.gov/positions-and-awards/#dialog |website=Hudson.house.gov |publisher=Team Hudson |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n- Order of the Longleaf Pine\n- Distinguished Alumni Award, UNC Charlotte\n- Distinguished Public Service Award, Kappa Alpha Order\n- Smith Province Court of Honor, Kappa Alpha Order\n- Friend of the Farmer Award, Farm Bureau \n- Congressional Trap, Skeet and Sporting Clays Champion 2017\n- Award for Conservative Excellence, American Conservative Union \n- True Blue Award, Family Research Council\n- Spirit of Enterprise Award, Chamber of Commerce \n- Guardian of Small Business Award, National Federation of Independent Business\n- Thomas Jefferson Award, International Foodservice Distributors Association\n- Legislator of the Year, that one EMS group\n- Legislator of the Year, that other EMS group\n- NC Young Republican Man of the Year, 1998\n- National Journal-Hotline Political Pursuit Fan Favorite Award\n\n===President Trump's travel ban executive order===\nHudson supported President [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] to impose a temporary ban on entry to the U.S. to citizens of seven Muslim-majority countries. He stated that \"At a time of grave security threats, President Trump is right to pause the flow of refugees from countries where terrorism is rampant until we can properly vet them and implement additional screening for individuals traveling to and from these countries.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|title=Coffman, Gardner join Republicans against President Trump's travel ban; here's where the rest stand|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/01/29/republicans-on-trump-travel-ban/|website=Denver Post |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|United States}}\n*[http://hudson.house.gov/ Congressman Richard Hudson] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.richardhudsonforcongress.com/ Richard Hudson for Congress]\n*{{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/North_Carolina/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Richard_Hudson_%5BR-8%5D|Richard Hudson}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=H001067 | votesmart=136448 | fec=H2NC08185 | congress=richard-hudson/2140 }}\n* {{C-SPAN|richardhudson}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Larry Kissell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from North Carolina|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br />from [[North Carolina's 8th congressional district]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[George Holding]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=206th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jared Huffman]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NC-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 113th\u2013115th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[United States congressional delegations from North Carolina|North Carolina]]}}\n{{USCongRep/NC/113}}\n{{USCongRep/NC/114}}\n{{USCongRep/NC/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hudson, Richard}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Cabarrus County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Franklin, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:United States congressional aides]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{update|date=February 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2013}}\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Richard Hudson\n|image       = Richard Hudson official congressional photo.jpg\n|state       = [[North Carolina]]\n|district    = {{ushr|NC|8|8th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2013\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Larry Kissell]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1971|11|4}}\n|birth_place = [[Franklin, Virginia|Franklin]], [[Virginia]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Renee Hudson\n|education   = [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n|website     = {{url|hudson.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Richard Lane Hudson''' (born November 4, 1971) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] for [[North Carolina's 8th congressional district]] since 2013. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nHudson was born in [[Franklin, Virginia]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/richard-hudson--NC-H|title=Richard Hudson - Candidate for U.S. President, Republican Nomination - Election 2012|website=WSJ.com|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> but has lived in the [[Charlotte]] area since childhood.  He graduated from [[Myers Park High School]] in 1990, and from the [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]] in 1996,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=H001067|title=HUDSON, Richard - Biographical Information|website=bioguide.congress.gov|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> where he became a member of [[Kappa Alpha Order]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Congressman Richard Hudson|url=http://www.kappaalphaorder.org/2013/01/kas-in-public-service/hudson|publisher=Kappa Alpha Order|accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref> He has a bachelor's degree in political science and history, and served as student body president and president of the College Republicans.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Early career ==\nActive in politics for many years, Hudson served as district director for 8th District Congressman [[Robin Hayes]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncheroes.org/congressman-richard-hudson/|title=Congressman Richard Hudson {{!}} North Carolina Heroes' Fund|website=www.ncheroes.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> from 1999 to 2005.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thepilot.com/news/hudson-mills-vie-for-congressional-seat/article_0c321f38-8fde-11e6-a991-33c09f175c65.html|title=Hudson, Mills Vie for Congressional Seat|last=Editor|first=David Sinclair/Managing|work=The Pilot Newspaper|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en}}</ref>  At various times, he served on the staffs of Republicans [[Virginia Foxx]], [[John Carter (Texas)|John Carter]] and [[Mike Conaway]].<ref name=\":1\" /> He also served as communications director for the North Carolina Republican Party in the mid-1990s.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1996 he worked for Richard Vinroot's campaign for governor, and as campaign manager for Pat McCrory's run for governor in 2008.<ref name=\":0\" /> Hudson was the president of Cabarrus Marketing Group, a small business consulting and marketing company he started in 2011 and dissolved upon his election to Congress.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Richard Hudson, Official portrait, 113th Congress.jpg|thumb|Hudson during the [[113th United States Congress|113th Congress]]]]\n\n===2012 election===\nHudson ran for Congress in North Carolina's 8th congressional district. He won the Republican primary runoff on July 17, 2012, with 64% of the vote against opponent [[Scott Keadle]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Hudson to take on Kissell in U.S. District 8|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/07/17/3388590/hudson-to-take-on-kissell-in-us.html|accessdate=1 September 2012|newspaper=Charlotte Observer|date=18 July 2012|author=David Perlmutt and Lukas Johnson|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130119021645/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/07/17/3388590/hudson-to-take-on-kissell-in-us.html|archivedate=19 January 2013}}</ref> and faced Democratic incumbent [[Larry Kissell]] in November.  The district had been made significantly more Republican in redistricting, losing most of its share of Charlotte and picking up several heavily Republican areas northeast of the city.\n\nRichard Hudson spoke at the [[2012 Republican National Convention]] in [[Tampa, Florida]] on August 28, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Concord hopeful Hudson speaks role at Republican National Convention|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/08/28/3485275/concord-hopeful-hudson-speaks.html|accessdate=1 September 2012|newspaper=Charlotte Observer|date=28 August 2012|author=Franco Ordo\u00f1ez|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130119015557/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/08/28/3485275/concord-hopeful-hudson-speaks.html|archivedate=19 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nHudson defeated Kissell with 54 percent of the vote to Kissell's 46 percent and took office in January 2013.\n\n===2014 election===\nHudson was opposed by Antonio Blue in the general election and won 64.9% to 35.1% <ref>{{cite web|url=http://ballotpedia.org/Richard_Hudson|title=Richard Hudson - Ballotpedia|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===2018 election===\nHudson defeated Democrat Frank McNeill in the general election, winning 55.3% of the vote to McNeill's 44.7% <ref>{{cite web |title=North Carolina Election Results 2018 |url=https://www.politico.com/election-results/2018/north-carolina/ |website=politico.com |publisher=Politico |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Livestock, Rural Development, and Credit|Subcommittee on Livestock, Rural Development, and Credit]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]]\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training|Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Oversight, Investigations, and Management|Subcommittee on Oversight, Investigations, and Management]]\n*'''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation sponsored===\n* EPA et al. Appropriations Act, 2017 ({{USBill|114|HR|5538}}) Rep. Hudson proposed two amendments to (a) prohibit any of the funds appropriated to the EPA be used for any firearms or ammunition and (b) prohibit any of the funds appropriated to the EPA be used for employee or officer official travel by airplane.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/tipsheets/morning-energy/2016/07/let-the-wotus-court-fights-commence-215231|title=Let the WOTUS court fights commence!|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Hudson sponsored a bill requiring the [[Transportation Security Administration]] (TSA) to develop a comprehensive technology acquisition plan.<ref name=\"techreform1\">{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House to push tech reform at TSA |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/technology/191721-house-to-push-tech-reform-at-tsa|accessdate=4 December 2013|newspaper=The Hill|date=2 December 2013}}</ref> The [[Government Accountability Office]] and the [[Department of Homeland Security Office of Inspector General]] each found that the TSA's lack of a technology acquisition plan led to waste, excessive costs, and security failures.<ref name=\"techreform1\" /> The bill passed both Houses of Congress, becoming law on 12/18/2012.\n* Hudson sponsored a bill to improve airport security in reaction to the [[2013 Los Angeles International Airport shooting]].<ref name=\"LATweikel\">{{cite news|last1=Weikel|first1=Dan|title=House passes bill to improve airport security in wake of LAX shooting|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-airport-security-bill-20140722-story.html|accessdate=23 July 2014|publisher=LA Times|date=22 July 2014}}</ref> The bill was reintroduced by Rep. John Katko and became law in the 114th Congress.\n\n==Former Political positions==\n{{expand section|date=April 2019}}\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hudson |first1=Richard |title=Congressman Richard Hudson |url=https://hudson.house.gov/positions-and-awards/#dialog |website=Hudson.house.gov |publisher=Team Hudson |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n- Deputy Chairman, NRCC 2015-2016\n- Recruitment Chairman, NRCC 2015-2016\n- Agriculture Policy Chairman, House Republican Policy Committee 2015-2016\n- Chairman, that group that teaches women how to run for office\n- Rowan-Cabarrus Community College, Board of Trustees\n- UNC Charlotte Alumni Association, Board of Directors\n- UNC Charlotte Kappa Alpha Order, Alumni Chapter President\n- West Cabarrus YMCA, Board of Managers\n- Concord Jaycees, Board of Directors \n- 2014 Grand Marshall, National Hot Rod Association 4-Wide Nationals\n\n==Awards==\n\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hudson |first1=Richard |title=Congressman Richard Hudson |url=https://hudson.house.gov/positions-and-awards/#dialog |website=Hudson.house.gov |publisher=Team Hudson |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n- Order of the Longleaf Pine\n- Distinguished Alumni Award, UNC Charlotte\n- Distinguished Public Service Award, Kappa Alpha Order\n- Smith Province Court of Honor, Kappa Alpha Order\n- Friend of the Farmer Award, Farm Bureau \n- Congressional Trap, Skeet and Sporting Clays Champion 2017\n- Award for Conservative Excellence, American Conservative Union \n- True Blue Award, Family Research Council\n- Spirit of Enterprise Award, Chamber of Commerce \n- Guardian of Small Business Award, National Federation of Independent Business\n- Thomas Jefferson Award, International Foodservice Distributors Association\n- Legislator of the Year, that one EMS group\n- Legislator of the Year, that other EMS group\n- NC Young Republican Man of the Year, 1998\n- National Journal-Hotline Political Pursuit Fan Favorite Award\n\n===President Trump's travel ban executive order===\nHudson supported President [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] to impose a temporary ban on entry to the U.S. to citizens of seven Muslim-majority countries. He stated that \"At a time of grave security threats, President Trump is right to pause the flow of refugees from countries where terrorism is rampant until we can properly vet them and implement additional screening for individuals traveling to and from these countries.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite 