asking Another Hofmann Forgery\n | journal       = [[Journal of Mormon History]]\n | date          = Winter 2011\n | volume        = 37\n | issue         = 1\n | pages         = x-xiv\n | url           = http://digitalcommons.usu.edu/mormonhistory/vol37/iss1/1/\n}}.  Also published in the [[Utah Historical Quarterly]], [http://utahhistory.sdlhost.com/#/item/000000033000235/view Winter 2011 issue], pages 92\u201395.\n*{{Cite journal\n | last       = Turley\n | first      = Richard E. Jr\n | authormask = 2\n | title         = \"Epoch in Musical History\": The Mormon Tabernacle Choir's First Recordings\n | journal       = [[Utah Historical Quarterly]]\n | date          = Spring 2011\n | volume        = 79\n | issue         = 2\n | pages         = 100\u2013121\n | url           = http://utahhistory.sdlhost.com/#/item/000000033000246/view\n}}.\n*{{citation\n |last        = Turley\n |first       = Richard E. Jr\n |authormask  = 2\n |title       = Clash of the Legal Titans: The First Trial of John D. Lee July 20 to August 7, 1875\n |year        = 2014\n |series      = Juanita Brooks Lecture Series\n |number      = 31\n |publisher   = Dixie State College of Utah\n |location    = St. George\n |url         = https://library.dixie.edu/special_collections/Juanita%20Brooks%20lectures/2014%20-%20Clash%20of%20the%20Legal%20Titans.pdf\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140417002226/http://library.dixie.edu/special_collections/Juanita%20Brooks%20lectures/2014%20-%20Clash%20of%20the%20Legal%20Titans.pdf\n |archivedate = April 17, 2014\n}}.\n*{{cite journal\n | last       = Turley\n | first      = Richard E. Jr\n | authormask = 2\n | author2       = Cannon, Jeffrey G.\n | title       = A Faithful Band: Moses Mahlangu and the First Soweto Saints\n | journal     = [[BYU Studies]]\n | year        = 2016\n | volume      = 55\n | issue       = 1\n | pages       = 8\u201338\n | url         = https://byustudies.byu.edu/content/faithful-band-moses-mahlangu-and-first-soweto-saints\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n===Other===\n*{{Cite thesis\n | author        = Turley, Theodore\n | editor        = Turley, Richard E. Jr\n | title         = Theodore Turley: Mission Journal, 1839-1840\n | publisher     = [[Brigham Young University]]\n | location      = Provo, Utah\n | year          = 1982\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n | author        = Turley, Ida Elizabeth Eyring\n | editor        = Turley, Richard E. Jr\n | title         = The Diary of Ida Elizabeth Eyring Turley: 1874-1952\n | publisher     = [[s.n.]]\n | location      = Salt Lake City\n | year          = 1997\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n | title         = Selected Collections from the Archives of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints\n | editor1-last  = Turley\n | editor1-first = Richard E. Jr\n |type=electronic resource, 2 volumes\n | publisher     = [[Brigham Young University Press]]\n | location      = Provo, Utah\n | year          = 2002\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n | author        = Turley, Richard E. Jr\n | title         = Why Can't I Forget My Sins?\n |type=sound recording\n | year          = 2006\n | publisher     = [[Deseret Book]]\n | location      = Salt Lake City, Utah\n | isbn          = 1-59038-553-5\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n2003-93778}}\n* [http://josephsmithpapers.org/projectTeam Biography] at Joseph Smith Papers Project website (accessed May 4, 2012)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turley, Richard E., Jr.}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mormon missionaries]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:American Latter Day Saint writers]]\n[[Category:American Mormon missionaries in Japan]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Utah]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mormon apologists]]\n[[Category:Official historians of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]\n[[Category:People from Fort Worth, Texas]]\n[[Category:Writers from Salt Lake City]]\n[[Category:J. Reuben Clark Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name          = Richard E. Turley Jr.\n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1956|2|18|mf=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]], [[Texas]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|body_discovered = \n|death_cause   = \n|resting_place = \n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|residence     = \n|nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n|ethnicity     = \n|citizenship   = \n|other_names   = \n|known_for     = Writings on LDS history<br/>LDS Church historical program\n|education     = English <small>([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] 1982) ([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] 1985)</small>\n|alma_mater    = [[Brigham Young University]]<br/>[[J. Reuben Clark Law School]]\n|employer      = [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]\n|occupation    = [[Assistant Church Historian]]\n|years_active  = 20\n|home_town     = \n|title         = \n|salary        = \n|networth      = \n|height        = \n|weight        = \n|term          = \n|predecessor   = \n|successor     = \n|party         = \n|opponents     =\n|boards        = \n|spouse        = Shirley Swensen Turley\n|partner       = \n|children      = 6\n|parents       = Richard E. Turley Sr.\n|relations     = Theodore Turley\n|callsign      = \n|signature     = \n|website       = \n|footnotes     = \n}}\n'''Richard Eyring \"Rick\" Turley Jr.''' (born February 18, 1956)<ref name=devotee>{{cite news | author=Lloyd, R. Scott | title=History devotee has Church's chronicles under his watchcare | date=October 17, 1992  | work=[[Church News]] | publisher=[[Deseret News]] | location=Salt Lake City, Utah | url=https://www.thechurchnews.com/archive/1992-10-17/history-devotee-has-churchs-chronicles-under-his-watchcare-4407 | accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> is an [[United States|American]] [[historian]] and [[genealogist]], and an [[Assistant Church Historian]] of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church). On April 26, 2016, the church announced that he would succeed [[Michael Otterson]] as the managing director of the church's Public Affairs Department, effective September 1, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/3821646-155/assistant-church-historian-to-oversee-mormon|title=Assistant church historian to oversee Mormon public affairs|last=Tribune|first=Peggy Fletcher Stack  The Salt Lake|website=The Salt Lake Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nTurley was born in [[Fort Worth, Texas]], to Richard and Betty Jean Nickle Turley.<ref name=devotee/> His father, a [[nuclear engineer]], [[scientist]] and [[Professors in the United States|professor]], would later become a [[mission president]] and [[general authority]] of the LDS Church.<ref>{{cite web | author=Lewis, William O. | title=Richard Eyring Turley, Sr. | work=Grampa Bill's General Authority Pages | url=http://www.gapages.com/turlere1.htm | accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref>\n\nTurley attended high school in [[Salt Lake City]], [[Utah]], when he met Shirley Swensen. They would later marry in the [[Salt Lake Temple]] and have six children. Turley aspired to be a [[lawyer]], by his father's urging, and an [[Institute of Religion]] teacher, by his deep personal interest in [[History of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|LDS Church history]]. From 1975 to 1977, Turley served as an [[LDS missionary]] to the [[Japan]] [[Tokyo]] [[Mission (LDS Church)|Mission]].<ref name=devotee/>\n\nAfter returning from Japan, Turley studied at [[Brigham Young University]] (BYU) as a [[Spencer W. Kimball]] Scholar, receiving a [[B. A.]] in English in 1982.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Cracroft, Richard H. | authorlink=Richard H. Cracroft | title=Historical Miscellanea | date=Fall 2008 | journal=BYU Magazine | publisher=Brigham Young University | location=Provo, Utah | url=http://magazine.byu.edu/?act=view&a=2305 | accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> Then, at BYU's [[J. Reuben Clark Law School]], he was editor of the [[law review]] and elected to the [[Order of the Coif]]. Upon graduation in April 1985, Turley received the [[Hugh B. Brown]] Barrister's Award for top classroom performance.<ref name=devotee/><ref name=newsroombio>{{cite web | title=Biography - Richard E. Turley Jr. | work=Newsroom | date=March 12, 2008 | publisher=LDS Church | location=Salt Lake City, Utah | url=https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/ldsnewsroom/eng/news-releases-stories/biography-richard-e-turley-jr | accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref>\n\n===Church employment===\nAfter passing the Utah State [[Bar examination]], Turley practiced law briefly before being hired by the LDS Church in January 1986. He was appointed Assistant Managing Director of the Historical Department, to replace the retiring [[Earl Olson]].<ref name=devotee/><ref name=victims>{{cite book | author=Turley, Richard E., Jr. | title=Victims: The LDS Church and the Mark Hofmann Case | pages=237 | year=1992 | publisher=[[University of Illinois Press]] | location=Urbana, Illinois | url=https://books.google.com/?id=IqrDDrWR_X4C&pg=PA237 | accessdate=2008-12-09 | isbn=978-0-252-01885-5}}</ref>\n\nAt this time, the department was already heavily involved in the investigation of [[Mark Hofmann]], the historical documents forger who attempted to hide his fraud by murder during the previous October.<ref name=devotee/> Turley's legal training helped the department which had examined and acquired several Hoffman forgeries (though some argued it was to hide their controversy).<ref name=victims/>\n\nWatching the case unfold in the press and in books, Turley felt misconceptions lingered from the media frenzy. To tell the story from the perspectives of the murder victims and the LDS Church (which Turley believed had been misrepresented) he published ''Victims: The LDS Church and the Mark Hofmann Case'' in 1992 through the [[University of Illinois Press]]. Though he wrote the book without church direction, his trusted position granted him church leaders' support and access to interviews, diaries, journals, memoranda, and other records.<ref name=devotee/>\n\n===Expanded role===\nTurley was appointed Managing Director of the Historical Department in 1989,<ref>[[John K. Carmack]] was Managing Director until 1989 (see [http://eom.byu.edu/index.php/Historians%2C_Church this article] from ''[[Encyclopedia of Mormonism]]''), which is when Turley was referred to as Managing Director in {{cite news | author=Thompson, Jan | title=Historian Pursuing 'Untold' Side of Hofmann Tale | date=May 27, 1989 | work=[[Deseret News]] | pages=B1 | url=http://archive.deseretnews.com/archive/print/48697/HISTORIAN-PURSUING-UNTOLD-SIDE-OF-HOFMANN-TALE.html | accessdate=2009-08-26 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and in 1996 he also became Managing Director of the Family History Department. While over the family history department Turley oversaw the launching of [[familysearch.org]].\n\nIn 2000, the Family History and Church History departments merged into the Family and Church History Department, over which Turley remained as Managing Director.<ref>{{cite news | title=Family History, History departments joined | date=June 10, 2000  | work=[[Church News]] | publisher=[[Deseret News]] | location=Salt Lake City, Utah | url=https://www.thechurchnews.com/archive/2000-06-10/family-history-history-departments-joined-17806 | accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref>\n\nIn these roles, Turley oversaw the [[Church Archives]], the [[Church History Library]], and the [[Museum of Church History and Art]], the [[Family History Library]], the FamilySearch Center, the [[Granite Mountain Records Vault]], and over 4,000 branch [[Family History Center (LDS Church)|family history centers]]. These comprise one of the largest collections of [[Mormon history]], [[Western United States|western]] history, and [[genealogy]] in the world.<ref name=newsroombio/> As a person of authority in LDS history and past defender of the church in the Hofmann controversy, Turley later became one of three official LDS Church respondents to a popular 2003 book critical of Mormonism, ''[[Under the Banner of Heaven]]'' by [[Jon Krakauer]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Church Response to Jon Krakauer's Under the Banner of Heaven | date=June 27, 2003 | work=Newsroom | publisher=LDS Church | url=https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/ldsnewsroom/eng/commentary/church-response-to-jon-krakauer-s-under-the-banner-of-heaven | accessdate=2009-10-11}}</ref>\n\n===Digital projects===\nIn the department, Turley managed several notable electronic projects.  [[FamilySearch]], a massive genealogical [[database]] [[website]], was launched in 1999. Other records were also released on [[CD-ROM]], including the ''[[Freedman\u2019s Bank]]'' (of [[African-American]] records), the ''Mormon Immigration Index'', ''European Vital Records Indexes'', and 1880s [[census]]es, including the ''1881 British Census'', which won the Besterman/McColvin Award from the [[Chartered Institute of Library and Information Professionals|Library Association of Great Britain]].<ref name=newsroombio/> For these efforts, and restoring several LDS historic sites, Turley received the [[Historic Preservation Medal]] from the [[Daughters of the American Revolution]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite news | author=Hart, John L. | title=Preserve roots to protect collective memory | date=May 1, 2004  | work=[[Church News]] | publisher=[[Deseret News]] | location=Salt Lake City, Utah | url=https://www.thechurchnews.com/archive/2004-05-01/preserve-roots-to-protect-collective-memory-25326 | accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, [[BYU Press]] published ''Selected Collections From the Archives of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints'', which Turley edited. On 74 [[DVD]]s, this released numerous important and rare early documents of the church, which some scholars and historians called \"the most important event in modern Mormon publishing,\"<ref>{{cite web | author=Kenney, Scott | title=Selected Collections Review | work=Saints Without Halos | url=http://saintswithouthalos.com/ss/sc.phtml | accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> and \"an achievement of such significance that no praise, no matter how effusive, seems sufficiently laudatory.\"<ref>{{cite web | author=Bergera, Gary James | title=MHA 2003 Book Reviews Published in the Journal of Mormon History | publisher=[[Mormon History Association]] | url=http://www.mhahome.org/pubs/book_reviews_2003.php#turley | accessdate=2008-12-09 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231034822/http://www.mhahome.org/pubs/book_reviews_2003.php#turley | archive-date=2008-12-31 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Assistant Church Historian===\nMore changes came to the department after [[Marlin K. Jensen]] became [[Church Historian]] in 2005. The department again staffed professional researchers, the [[Joseph Smith Papers Project]] sharply expanded, and a new [[Church History Library]] was announced.\n\nOn March 12, 2008, the Family and Church History Department announced it was becoming two departments again: the Family History Department and the Church History Department.<ref>{{cite web | author=Jared T. | title=Breaking News: Changes in Family and Church History Department Organization | date=March 12, 2008 | work=Juvenile Instructor (blog) | url=http://www.juvenileinstructor.org/breaking-news-changes-in-church-history-department-organization/ | accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> In addition, Turley became the [[Assistant Church Historian]],<ref name=newsroom>{{cite web | title=Richard E. Turley Jr. Named Assistant Church Historian and Recorder | date=March 12, 2008 | work=Newsroom | publisher=LDS Church | location=Salt Lake City, Utah | url=https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/ldsnewsroom/eng/news-releases-stories/richard-e-turley-jr-named-assistant-church-historian-and-recorder | accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> an ecclesiastical position that was unfilled for over 25 years. [[Steven L. Olsen]], the department's Associate Managing Director, took Turley's old position of Managing Director.<ref>{{cite news | author= | title=U.S. landmark | date=April 5, 2008 | work=[[Church News]] | publisher=[[Deseret News]] | location=Salt Lake City, Utah | url=https://www.thechurchnews.com/archive/2008-04-05/u-s-landmark-31600 | accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref>\n\nFor his contributions to public history while overseeing the church's archives, records, museums, and historic sites, Turley was awarded the 2013 Herbert Feis Award from the [[American Historical Association]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Herbert Feis Award Recipients | publisher=American Historical Association | url=https://www.historians.org/awards-and-grants/past-recipients/herbert-feis-award-recipients | accessdate=2014-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author=Tad Walch | title=LDS Church historian wins major award, credits church employees and missionaries | date=January 10, 2014 | work=[[Deseret News]] | url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865593893/LDS-Church-historian-wins-major-award-credits-church-employees-and-missionaries.html?pg=all | accessdate=2014-12-11}}</ref>\n\n===Public Affairs Department===\nIn April 2016, the church announced that Turley would move from the Church History Department and become the successor to Michael Otterson as the managing director of the church's Public Affiars Department.<ref>[https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/additional-resource/biography-richard-e-turley-jr LDS Newsroom announcement of Turley going to Public Affairs Department leadership]</ref> The two worked closely together through a transition period until Otterson's departure in August, to accept an assignment as a [[temple president]].<ref>[https://www.heraldextra.com/news/local/faith/richard-e-turley-jr-named-as-new-director-of-lds/article_4cc065ce-9a90-58b1-92b3-10275a1898c7.html ''Daily Herald'' article on Turley replacing Otterson]</ref><ref>[http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=3821646&itype=CMSID ''Salt Lake Tribune'' article on Turley's appointment]</ref><ref>[https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865652971/Assistant-LDS-Church-historian-will-be-new-head-of-LDS-Church-Public-Affairs.html ''Deseret News'' article on Turley's appointment to the Public Affairs Department managing director position]</ref> Among other events and activities in this new role, Turley traveled to the Philippines in December 2017 where he gave three devotionals on Church History.<ref>[https://www.mormonnewsroom.ph/article/church-managing-director-for-public-affairs-visits-the-philippines LDS Newsroom article on Turley's journey to the Philippines]</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2017, Turley was given the [[Mormon Historic Sites Foundation]] Junius Wells Award.<ref>[http://mormonhistoricsites.org/richard-e-turley-jr/ report on Turley receiving award]</ref>\n\n==Organizations==\nTurley has been involved with several genealogical and historical organizations.\n* Historic Sites Committee (LDS Church)<ref name=newsroom/>\n* President of the [[Genealogical Society of Utah]] (2000\u20132008),<ref name=newsroom/>\n* The [[Joseph Smith Papers]] editorial board<ref name=jspp>{{cite web | title=Editorial Board Bios | publisher=[[The Joseph Smith Papers]] | url=http://josephsmithpapers.org/EditorialBios.htm#RETurley | accessdate=2008-12-09 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120162230/http://www.josephsmithpapers.org/EditorialBios.htm#RETurley | archive-date=2008-11-20 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Executive Committee of the [[Joseph Fielding Smith Institute for Latter-day Saint History]]<ref>{{cite journal | title=About the Contributors | journal=The BYU Family Historian | volume=1 | issue=1 | date=Fall 2002 | page=54 | publisher=Center for Family History and Genealogy, [[Brigham Young University]] | location=Provo, Utah | url=http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/u?/BYUFamilyHistorian,428 | accessdate=2009-03-26}}</ref>\n* General editor of The Journals of George Q. Cannon series<ref name=jspp/>\n* President of the Salt Lake City Chapter of the [[Sons of Utah Pioneers]] (1990)<ref>{{cite news | author=Llyod, R. Scott | title=Seeking to identify pioneers | date=July 21, 1990 | work=[[Church News]] | publisher=[[Deseret News]] | location=Salt Lake City, Utah | url=https://www.thechurchnews.com/archive/1990-07-21/seeking-to-identify-pioneers-2302 | accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref>\n* Vice President of the Small Museum Administrators Committee, [[American Association of Museums]]<ref name=newsroombio/>\n* Utah State Historical Records Advisory Board, [[National Historical Publications and Records Commission]]<ref name=newsroombio/>\n* Copyright Task Force, [[Society of American Archivists]]<ref name=newsroombio/>\n* Moderator for [[The Worlds of Joseph Smith]] conference in 2005<ref>{{cite news | author=Lloyd, R. Scott | title=Prophet's worlds: Joseph Smith conference at Library of Congress | date=May 14, 2005  | work=[[Church News]] | publisher=[[Deseret News]] | location=Salt Lake City, Utah | url=https://www.thechurchnews.com/archive/2005-05-14/prophets-worlds-27133 | accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref>\n\n==Historical philosophy==\nIn 1992, Turley commented on how Mormon history can affect the faith of LDS Church members:<blockquote>Some people may wish to base their faith on historical evidence. While historical information can be useful, interesting and can provide insights to individuals, I don't think that it's the sure foundation of faith. The sure foundation of faith is spiritual and not physical. ... [T]he more an individual learns about the history of the Church, the greater that individual's understanding will be of the overall picture. Thus, every piece of evidence will be viewed against the total picture. Otherwise, people who do not have much knowledge of Church history may find themselves being tossed to and fro by tidbits from the past.<ref name=devotee/></blockquote>\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books===\n*{{cite book\n | author        = Turley, Richard E., Jr.\n | title         = Victims: The LDS Church and the Mark Hofmann Case\n | publisher     = [[University of Illinois Press]]\n | location      = Urbana, Illinois\n | year          = 1992\n | isbn          = 0-252-01885-0\n | url           = https://books.google.com/books?id=IqrDDrWR_X4C&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n | author1       = \u2014\u2014\n | author2       = Littke, Lael\n | title         = Stories from the Life of Joseph Smith\n | year          = 2003\n | publisher     = [[Deseret Book]]\n | location      = Salt Lake City, Utah\n | isbn          = 1-57008-915-9\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n | last1         = Walker\n | first1        = Ronald W.\n | author1-link  = Ronald W. Walker\n | last2         = Turley\n | first2        = Richard E., Jr.\n | last3         = Leonard\n | first3        = Glen M.\n | author3-link  = Glen M. Leonard\n | title         = [[Massacre at Mountain Meadows]]\n | year          = 2008\n | publisher     = [[Oxford University Press]]\n | location      = Oxford; New York\n | isbn          = 978-0-19-516034-5\n}}.\n*{{cite book\n | author1       = Turley, Richard E., Jr.\n | author2       = Slaughter, William W.\n | title         = How We Got the Book of Mormon\n | publisher     = [[Deseret Book]]\n | location      = Salt Lake City\n | year          = 2011\n | isbn          = 9781609080624\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author1       = \u2014\u2014\n | author2       = \u2014\u2014\n | title         = How We Got the Doctrine and Covenants\n | publisher     = [[Deseret Book]]\n | location      = Salt Lake City\n | year          = 2012\n | isbn          = 9781609071509\n}}\n\n===Edited volumes===\n*{{Cite book\n | author        = Cannon, George Q.\n | authorlink    = George Q. Cannon\n | editor1-last  = Cannon\n | editor1-first = Adrian W.\n | editor2-last  = Turley\n | editor2-first = Richard E., Jr.\n | editor3-last  = Landon\n | editor3-first = Michael\n | title         = The Journals of George Q. Cannon: To California in '49\n | publisher     = [[Deseret Book]]\n | location      = Salt Lake City, Utah\n | year          = 1999\n | isbn          = 1-57345-465-6\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n | editor1-last  = Turley\n | editor1-first = Richard E. Jr.\n | editor2-last  = Walker\n | editor2-first = Ronald W.\n | editor2-link  = Ronald W. Walker\n | title         = Mountain Meadows Massacre: The Andrew Jenson and David H. Morris Collections\n | year          = 2009\n | publisher     = [[Brigham Young University Press]] and [[University of Utah Press]]\n | location      = Provo and Salt Lake City\n | series        = Documents in Latter-day Saint History\n | isbn          = 978-0-8425-2723-1\n}}.\n*{{Cite book\n | editor1       = \u2014\u2014\n | editor2-last  = Harper\n | editor2-first = Steven C.\n | editor2-link  = Steven C. Harper\n | title         = Preserving the History of the Latter-day Saints\n | year          = 2010\n | publisher     = [[Religious Studies Center]], [[Brigham Young University]] and [[Deseret Book]]\n | location      = Provo and Salt Lake City, Utah\n | series        = Church History Symposium\n | isbn          = 978-0-8425-2777-4\n}}.\n*{{Cite book\n | author-last   = Smith\n | author-first  = Joseph, Jr.\n | author-link   = Joseph Smith\n | editor1-last  = Lorimer\n | editor1-first = Riley M.\n | editor2-last  = Turley\n | editor2-first = Richard E. Jr.\n | editor3-last  = Jensen\n | editor3-first = Robin Scott\n | title         = Published Revelations\n | series        = The Joseph Smith Papers: Revelations and Translations\n | volume        = 2\n | year          = 2011\n | publisher     = [[Church Historian's Press]]\n | location      = Salt Lake City, Utah\n | isbn          = 9781606419427\n}}.\n*{{cite book\n | editor1       = Turley, Richard E. Jr.\n | editor2       = Chapman, Brittany A.\n 